00:17:56,756 --> 00:18:00,276 A:middle
then tomorrow, when they
score 5,000 points, let's say,

415
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=MPEGTS:181083,LOCAL:00:00:00,000

416
00:18:00,606 --> 00:18:04,916 A:middle
5,000 isn't better than 10,000,
so 10,000 is going to remain

417
00:18:04,916 --> 00:18:08,206 A:middle
on the all-time time span
for that leaderboard.

418
00:18:09,056 --> 00:18:10,876 A:middle
Or what if you want to
implement a leaderboard

419
00:18:10,876 --> 00:18:13,416 A:middle
where scores can both go
up and down over the course

420
00:18:13,416 --> 00:18:16,366 A:middle
of people playing your
game, like batting average.

421
00:18:16,626 --> 00:18:18,716 A:middle
If you want to track your
player's batting average

422
00:18:18,836 --> 00:18:20,216 A:middle
over a season, that's going

423
00:18:20,216 --> 00:18:22,926 A:middle
to not just be monotonically
increasing or decreasing,

424
00:18:23,186 --> 00:18:24,916 A:middle
it's actually going
to be increasing

425
00:18:24,916 --> 00:18:26,566 A:middle
or decreasing over time.

426
00:18:26,776 --> 00:18:29,376 A:middle
So that's what a Most Recent
Score Leaderboard allows you

427
00:18:29,376 --> 00:18:30,126 A:middle
to do.

428
00:18:30,726 --> 00:18:33,246 A:middle
Most Recent Score Leaderboards,
they're just an alternative

429
00:18:33,246 --> 00:18:34,586 A:middle
to Best Score Leaderboards.

430
00:18:35,046 --> 00:18:37,306 A:middle
And the way that they function
